<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="868" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d868">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.711/3</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-20">
                                <hi rend="italic">October 20, 1914</hi>.</date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 4:35 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>866. <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> has learned
                            through commercial correspondence passing through censor that
                            arrangements appear to be in progress by which general correspondence
                            with Germany shall pass through American Consulate General at Rotterdam.
                            He asks me to bring this to your notice with a view to adequate steps
                            being taken to prevent the confidence of our consular officers being
                            abused. Despatch follows.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>